  "output": "## Findings\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraper/CLI (no React/frontend — no re-render concerns apply). Runs are short-lived (triggered by GitHub Actions cron, per `.github/workflows/scrape.yaml`), so classic long-process memory leaks don't apply either. I've mapped the requested categories onto their real Python equivalents.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-74` (real, significant)\n\n`Store.diff()` runs one `SELECT` per job, sequentially, inside a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nFor a run pulling thousands of jobs (Amazon/Microsoft/Apple boards are capped at 40 pages × 10-20/page), that's thousands of round-trips to SQLite instead of one. Fix: batch-fetch existing hashes, diff in memory, then batch-write:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 900):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i+900]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update({r[\"key\"]: r[\"content_hash\"] for r in self.conn.execute(q, chunk)})\n\n    new, changed, unchanged_rows, insert_rows, update_rows = [], [], [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); update_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            unchanged_rows.append({\"now\": now, \"key\": job.key})\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    if insert_rows: cur.executemany(\"INSERT INTO jobs (...) VALUES (:key,...)\", insert_rows)\n    if update_rows: cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET ... WHERE key=:key\", update_rows)\n    if unchanged_rows: cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", unchanged_rows)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\n### 2. Redundant deep-copy in `models.py:71-75` (`Job.to_row`)\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)     # recursively deep-copies EVERY field, including `raw`\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then throws the copy away\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict()` recursively walks and deep-copies nested dicts/lists. `raw` holds the entire unprocessed API payload (can be a large nested dict for Apple/Google/Workday) and is deep-copied on every call just to be discarded a line later. This runs once per job on every `_insert`/`_update` — i.e., potentially thousands of times per run. Fix — skip `raw` before copying:\n\n```python\nfrom dataclasses import fields\n\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = {f.name: getattr(self, f.name) for f in fields(self) if f.name != \"raw\"}\n    d[\"key\"] = self.key\n    d[\"content_hash\"] = self.content_hash\n    return d\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` recomputed twice per changed job\n\n`Store.diff()` reads `job.content_hash` (a `@property` doing a `\"|\".join(...)` + `sha256`) for the comparison, then `_update()` calls `job.to_row()` which recomputes the same hash from scratch. Cheap per-call, but doubled for every changed job for no reason — compute once and thread it through (naturally falls out of the batched rewrite above, since `to_row()` is only called once per job now).\n\n### 4. Repeated regex (re)compilation — `filters.py:11-27` (closest analog to \"unnecessary re-render\")\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # rebuilt every call\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # rebuilt every call\n```\n\n`filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per fetched job, and `_compile()` rebuilds the include/exclude pattern lists (with `re.escape` + list comprehension) from scratch every single time, even though the keyword lists are invariant for the whole run. CPython's internal `re` cache blunts the worst of the recompilation cost, but the list/escape work still repeats needlessly across potentially thousands of jobs. Fix — compile once outside the per-job loop:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = ...\n    include_pat = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude_pat = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in rules.get(\"locations\") or []]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include_pat, exclude_pat, locations, cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, include_pat, exclude_pat, locations, cutoff) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude_pat and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude_pat):\n        return False\n    if include_pat and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include_pat):\n        return False\n    if locations:\n        loc = job.location.lower()\n        if not any(l in loc for l in locations):\n            return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 5. Blocking I/O inside an async pipeline — `notify.py` + `pipeline.py:42-44`\n\n`pipeline.run()` is `async`, but `dispatch()` calls `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms` (all synchronous `httpx.post`) and `notify_email` (blocking `smtplib`) sequentially. This blocks the event loop thread for the duration of every network call. Since nothing else runs concurrently at that point in this CLI, it's not currently a bottleneck — but it's the \"would bite you if this pipeline ever grows a concurrent step\" trap. Low priority; worth a comment if not fixing now, or swap to `httpx.AsyncClient` + `asyncio.gather` if dispatch ever needs to be concurrent with other work.\n\n### 6. Caching — no real opportunity, and that's correct here\n\nI looked for HTTP response caching (ETag/If-None-Match) across `fetchers.py`, but this is a scraper whose entire purpose is detecting *new* content each run — caching responses would defeat the point. No change recommended there. The one legitimate caching candidate is memoizing `Job.content_hash`/`posted_dt` (`@property`, recomputed on every access) via `functools.cached_property`, but `Job` uses `slots=True` without a slot for the cache, so this only pays off after fixing #2/#3 collapse the call count to once-per-job anyway — not worth the slots refactor on its own.\n\n### Memory leaks\nNone found. Each pipeline run is a fresh, short-lived process (GitHub Actions cron per `.github/workflows/scrape.yaml`), `Store` connections are properly closed via context managers, and per-source `seen: set[str]` accumulators in `fetchers.py` are bounded by each source's own pagination and die with the process.\n\n## Priority\n1. **#1 (N+1 SQLite)** — biggest real win, straightforward fix.\n2. **#2 (`asdict` deep-copy of `raw`)** — cheap fix, removes real per-job overhead on large boards.\n3. **#4 (regex recompilation)** — cheap fix, same shape as #2.\n4. #3, #5 — minor/cosmetic; do opportunistically while touching the above.\n",
